PHASE 5 — SESSION MANAGEMENT
================================================================================
Goal: Owners can create, edit, activate/deactivate, and view sessions (events).
      The UI is server-rendered where possible.

--- 5.1  Session List Page (/sessions) ---
[ ] Server component: fetch sessions from Supabase using server client
[ ] Display: name, capacity, ticket count, tickets used, status, dates
[ ] "New Session" button → opens modal or navigates to /sessions/new
[ ] Role guard: only owners see this page (middleware enforces)

--- 5.2  Create Session API Route ---
[ ] POST /api/sessions:
      - Auth check (must be owner)
      - Zod validation: name, capacity, starts_at, ends_at, description
      - Insert into sessions table
      - Return created session
[ ] WHY: server-side insert ensures owner_id is set from the verified session,
    not from client-supplied data

--- 5.3  Session Detail Page (/sessions/[id]) ---
[ ] Show session metadata
[ ] Show ticket list (paginated, 50 per page)
[ ] Show: attendee name, status (used/unused), used_at, scanned_by
[ ] Action buttons: Generate Tickets, Export CSV, Deactivate Session

--- 5.4  Update / Delete Session API Routes ---
[ ] PATCH /api/sessions/[id]: validate owner owns session before update
[ ] DELETE /api/sessions/[id]: soft-delete (set is_active = false)
[ ] WHY: never hard-delete sessions — you need the audit trail

--- 5.5  Session Components ---
[ ] SessionCard component (reusable)
[ ] SessionForm component (create/edit, shared)
[ ] SessionStats component (capacity bar, usage %)
[ ] Confirm deactivation with a modal (destructive action warning)

--- 5.6  Phase 5 Verification Checklist ---
[ ] Owner can create a session with all fields
[ ] Session appears in list immediately
[ ] Capacity is enforced (cannot generate more tickets than capacity)
[ ] Deactivated session is not accessible to scanners
[ ] Scanner staff cannot access /sessions page

EXPECTED RESULT: Full session CRUD with server-side ownership enforcement.

================================================================================
PHASE 6 — STAFF / SCANNER MANAGEMENT
================================================================================
Goal: Owners invite scanner staff via email. Staff accept via a link. Staff
      accounts are scoped and revocable.

--- 6.1  Invite Staff API Route ---
[ ] POST /api/staff/invite:
      - Owner auth check
      - Zod: email, optional session_id (scoped invite), expires_in hours
      - Generate secure random token (use crypto.randomUUID())
      - Insert into staff_invitations
      - Send email with Supabase Auth inviteUserByEmail() OR custom link
      - Invitation link: /accept-invite?token=<uuid>
[ ] WHY: email invitations prevent self-registration by unknown parties

--- 6.2  Accept Invitation Page ---
[ ] GET /accept-invite?token=... :
      - Validate token exists and is not expired/used
      - Show form: full name + password
[ ] POST /api/staff/accept-invite:
      - Validate token again (double check, token can be replayed)
      - supabase.auth.admin.createUser({ email, password, role: 'scanner' })
      - Insert into profiles
      - Mark invitation as accepted (accepted_at = now())

--- 6.3  Staff List Page (/staff) ---
[ ] List all scanner profiles: name, email, is_active, created_at
[ ] Show last scan timestamp per staff member
[ ] Actions: Revoke access (set is_active = false)

--- 6.4  Revoke Access API Route ---
[ ] POST /api/staff/[id]/revoke:
      - Owner auth check
      - Set profiles.is_active = false
      - supabase.auth.admin.signOut(userId) (invalidate sessions)
[ ] WHY: disabling without sign-out leaves active tokens until expiry

--- 6.5  Middleware Scanner Active Check ---
[ ] On every scanner request, verify profiles.is_active = true
[ ] If false → sign out and redirect to /login with "Account suspended" message

--- 6.6  Phase 6 Verification Checklist ---
[ ] Owner sends invite → email received with valid link
[ ] Staff accepts invite → account created with role 'scanner'
[ ] Revoked staff cannot log in or make API calls
[ ] Staff list shows correct active/inactive state
[ ] Expired invitations are rejected gracefully

EXPECTED RESULT: Safe, revocable, invitation-only staff onboarding.

================================================================================
PHASE 7 — QR CODE GENERATION SYSTEM
================================================================================
Goal: Generate cryptographically unique QR codes per ticket. Store tokens
      securely. Never expose the raw token in the QR code plaintext.

--- 7.1  Ticket Generation API Route ---
[ ] POST /api/sessions/[id]/tickets/generate:
      - Owner auth check
      - Check session capacity vs existing ticket count
      - Accept: count (how many to generate), optional attendee CSV data
      - Generate `count` rows with:
          token: crypto.randomUUID()   (stored in DB)
          qr_payload: base64(sessionId + "." + token) or signed JWT
      - Bulk insert with supabase from('tickets').insert(rows)
      - Return list of ticket IDs (NOT raw tokens)
[ ] WHY: tokens are secret; expose only IDs to client for QR rendering

--- 7.2  Individual Ticket QR Endpoint ---
[ ] GET /api/tickets/[id]/qr:
      - Owner auth check
      - Fetch ticket token from DB (server only)
      - Generate QR code SVG/PNG using `qrcode` library (server-side)
      - Return image with Cache-Control: no-store
[ ] WHY: QR is generated server-side so the raw token is never in client memory

--- 7.3  QR Payload Format ---
[ ] Payload: JSON stringified { v: 1, t: "<token_uuid>" }
[ ] Optionally sign with HMAC-SHA256 using a server secret for tamper detection
[ ] Keep payload short — QR complexity grows with payload size
[ ] WHY: versioned payload allows format changes without breaking old codes

--- 7.4  Bulk Export ---
[ ] GET /api/sessions/[id]/tickets/export:
      - Returns PDF or ZIP of QR code images
      - Each QR labeled with attendee name if provided
      - Owner only
[ ] Use a library like pdfkit or jsPDF on server-side

--- 7.5  Ticket Generation UI ---
[ ] "Generate Tickets" button on session detail page
[ ] Input: quantity selector (1–capacity remaining)
[ ] Optional: CSV upload for attendee names/emails
[ ] Progress indicator for bulk generation (stream response)
[ ] After generation: show list with download QR button per ticket

--- 7.6  Phase 7 Verification Checklist ---
[ ] Can generate 1 ticket → QR code image renders correctly
[ ] Can generate 100 tickets in bulk (check for DB timeout)
[ ] QR token is NOT visible in browser DevTools network tab (server renders)
[ ] Generating beyond session capacity returns 400 error
[ ] Each ticket has a unique token (check DB constraint)

EXPECTED RESULT: Server-side QR generation with cryptographically unique,
non-guessable tokens. Client never touches raw token values.

================================================================================
PHASE 8 — QR SCANNING SYSTEM
================================================================================
Goal: Scanner staff use a mobile-friendly camera UI to scan QR codes. Scanning
      always calls the server — never validates on the frontend.

--- 8.1  Scanner Page UI (/scan) ---
[ ] Mobile-first, full-screen camera view
[ ] Use react-qr-reader or @zxing/browser for QR detection
[ ] Show status overlay (Ready / Scanning / Processing / Result)
[ ] Result states:
      ✅ Valid   — green overlay, attendee name, session name
      ❌ Used    — red overlay, "Already scanned at <time> by <staff>"
      ⏰ Expired — yellow overlay, "Ticket expired"
      ❓ Invalid — red overlay, "QR code not recognised"
[ ] Auto-reset to scan mode after 3 seconds
[ ] Haptic feedback on mobile (navigator.vibrate)
[ ] WHY: visual + haptic feedback reduces scanner error under pressure

--- 8.2  Scan API Route ---
[ ] POST /api/validate:
      - Scanner auth check (must be authenticated + is_active)
      - Rate limit: max 30 requests/minute per scanner (use Upstash or DB)
      - Zod: { payload: string }
      - Parse payload: extract token
      - Call validate_ticket(token, scanner_id) Postgres function
      - Return result to client
[ ] WHY: validation MUST be server-side — client cannot be trusted to
    determine if a ticket is valid

--- 8.3  Validation Response Format ---
[ ] Success:   { valid: true, attendee: string, session: string, scanned_at: string }
[ ] Used:      { valid: false, reason: "already_used", first_scan: string, first_scanner: string }
[ ] Expired:   { valid: false, reason: "expired" }
[ ] Not found: { valid: false, reason: "not_found" }

--- 8.4  Prevent Replay / Race Conditions ---
[ ] validate_ticket DB function uses:
      SELECT ... FOR UPDATE   (row-level lock)
      UPDATE tickets SET is_used = true WHERE id = ... AND is_used = false
      IF NOT FOUND → RETURN already_used result
[ ] All within a single transaction
[ ] WHY: without FOR UPDATE, two concurrent scans could both succeed

--- 8.5  Offline Consideration ---
[ ] Show "No internet" banner when offline
[ ] Do NOT implement offline validation (too risky for fraud)
[ ] Queue rejected scans for retry is acceptable for logging only

--- 8.6  Phase 8 Verification Checklist ---
[ ] Scanner page loads on mobile without errors
[ ] Camera permission prompt appears correctly
[ ] Valid QR scan returns success within 500ms
[ ] Two simultaneous scans of same QR → only one succeeds
[ ] Scan without internet → clear error message
[ ] Rate limit triggers after 30 rapid scans

EXPECTED RESULT: Reliable, fast, mobile-first scanning with server-side
validation and race-condition-proof one-time-use logic.

================================================================================
PHASE 9 — ONE-TIME VALIDATION LOGIC (DEEP DIVE)
================================================================================
Goal: Make it mathematically impossible to use a ticket twice, even under
      concurrent load from multiple scanners at the same event.

--- 9.1  Atomic DB Function (final implementation) ---
[ ] CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION validate_ticket(
      p_token UUID,
      p_scanner_id UUID
    ) RETURNS JSONB
    LANGUAGE plpgsql
    SECURITY DEFINER
    AS $$
    DECLARE
      v_ticket tickets%ROWTYPE;
      v_session sessions%ROWTYPE;
    BEGIN
      -- Lock the row immediately
      SELECT * INTO v_ticket
      FROM tickets
      WHERE token = p_token
      FOR UPDATE NOWAIT;

      -- Not found
      IF NOT FOUND THEN
        RETURN jsonb_build_object('valid', false, 'reason', 'not_found');
      END IF;

      -- Expired
      IF v_ticket.expires_at IS NOT NULL AND v_ticket.expires_at < now() THEN
        INSERT INTO scan_logs(ticket_id, session_id, scanned_by, scan_result)
        VALUES (v_ticket.id, v_ticket.session_id, p_scanner_id, 'expired');
        RETURN jsonb_build_object('valid', false, 'reason', 'expired');
      END IF;

      -- Already used
      IF v_ticket.is_used THEN
        INSERT INTO scan_logs(ticket_id, session_id, scanned_by, scan_result)
        VALUES (v_ticket.id, v_ticket.session_id, p_scanner_id, 'already_used');
        RETURN jsonb_build_object('valid', false, 'reason', 'already_used',
          'used_at', v_ticket.used_at);
      END IF;

      -- Mark as used
      UPDATE tickets
      SET is_used = true, used_at = now(), scanned_by = p_scanner_id
      WHERE id = v_ticket.id;

      -- Log success
      INSERT INTO scan_logs(ticket_id, session_id, scanned_by, scan_result)
      VALUES (v_ticket.id, v_ticket.session_id, p_scanner_id, 'success');

      -- Fetch session name
      SELECT * INTO v_session FROM sessions WHERE id = v_ticket.session_id;

      RETURN jsonb_build_object(
        'valid', true,
        'attendee_name', v_ticket.attendee_name,
        'session_name', v_session.name
      );
    END;
    $$;

[ ] WHY: FOR UPDATE NOWAIT acquires a row lock. If two transactions try to
    lock the same row simultaneously, the second gets an error immediately
    instead of waiting — preventing a double-success window.

--- 9.2  API Route Calls the Function ---
[ ] const { data } = await supabase.rpc('validate_ticket', {
      p_token: token,
      p_scanner_id: user.id
    })
[ ] Handle NOWAIT lock error (error code 55P03) → return 409 "Scan collision,
    try again" — the scanner should retry once

--- 9.3  Token Expiry Enforcement ---
[ ] If session.ends_at is set, set ticket.expires_at = session.ends_at on generation
[ ] Expiry is checked inside the DB function (source of truth)
[ ] WHY: client clocks cannot be trusted for expiry checks

--- 9.4  Phase 9 Verification Checklist ---
[ ] Load test: 10 concurrent POST /api/validate with same token
    → exactly 1 success, rest return already_used or collision
[ ] Expired ticket returns expired reason
[ ] scan_logs has one row per scan attempt (including failed ones)
[ ] No ticket can have is_used = false after a successful validate

